body:
To avoid the infinite loop in Scala 2, one needs to make MultiNodeSpec a class and to have it in a different package, then Scala 2 decides to generate a super-accessor instead of a regular method call for some reason:
```scala
package a {
  class MultiNodeSpec {
    protected def atStartup(): Unit = {
    }

    def beforeAll(): Unit = {
      atStartup()
    }
  }
}
package b {
  trait MultiNodeClusterSpec {
    self: a.MultiNodeSpec =>
  
    override protected def atStartup(): Unit = {
      self.atStartup()
    }
  }
}

class DownAllUnstable5NodeSpec extends a.MultiNodeSpec with b.MultiNodeClusterSpec

object Main extends App {
  new DownAllUnstable5NodeSpec().beforeAll()
}
```
To me, this looks like a bug in Scala 2: it's generating an accessor because atStartup in MultiNodeSpec is not accessible from package b, but in doing so it's breaking virtual dispatch. A likely fix would be to explicitly call `super.atStartup()` instead (assuming atStartup is defined in a common parent of MultiNodeSpec and MultiNodeClusterSpec), super-calls in traits are virtual, so this should resolve to the atStartup in MultiNodeSpec.
